    public static class TransformingRandomAccessSet.Bidi<I,O>
extends TransformingSet.Bidi<I,O>
implements RandomAccessSet<O>
    A transforming random access set that can transform values in both directions. Since this set can transform values in the other direction (output type -> input type), all operations are supported, including TransformingCollection.Bidi.add(Object) and TransformingCollection.Bidi.addAll(Collection).

    Several methods are overridden to use the reverse function before delegating to the underlying set. Since some of these interface methods actually accept any type of object (instead of requiring the set's element type), this implementation could result in ClassCastExceptions if objects with incorrect types are passed to them. These methods are TransformingCollection.Bidi.contains(Object), TransformingCollection.Bidi.containsAll(Collection), TransformingCollection.Bidi.remove(Object), TransformingCollection.Bidi.removeAll(Collection), and TransformingCollection.Bidi.retainAll(Collection).

    • Constructor Detail

      • Bidi

        public Bidi(RandomAccessSet<I> set,
            Function<? super I,? extends O> function1,
            Function<? super O,? extends I> function2)
        Constructs a new bidirectional transforming random access set. The two provided functions must be inverses of one another. In other words, for any object i in the input domain, i must equal function2.apply(function1.apply(i)). Similarly, for any object o in the output domain, o must equal function1.apply(function2.apply(o)).
        Parameters:
        set - the wrapped set
        function1 - transforms elements; "input" -> "output"
        function2 - the inverse of function1; "output" -> "input"

      • listIterator

        public ListIterator<O> listIterator()
        Description copied from interface: RandomAccessSet
        Returns a ListIterator for iterating over the set. The iterator will start off before the first element so the first call to next() returns the first element in the set. Iteration is in the same order as that of Set.iterator(), but allows for navigating both forwards and backwards in the set and for retrieving the indices of elements.

        Elements cannot be set or added using the returned iterator. These operations will throw UnsupportedOperationExceptions.

        Specified by:
